{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958042501/0241.xml":{"full_text":"Jhio Church Council\nCondemns Chamber\u2019s\n\u2018Right to Work Drive\nProtestant Churchmen Join Catholic\nBishops in Opposing Union Busting\nThe Ohio Council of Churches, an interdenomina\ntional group of Protestant churches, has taken a stand\nagainst a so-called \u201cright-to-work\u201d law for Ohio.\nThe Council thus has joined the Catholic Bishops of\nOhio and other clergymen in urging Ohioans to oppose\nthe campaign of the Ohio Chamber of Commerce for a\n\u201cright-to-work\u201d amendment to the Ohio Constitution.\nThe Council of Churches\nannounced its opposition to\ny\n1\nthe Ohio Chamber\u2019s proposal!\nat its semi-annual meeting in\nColumbus.\nCalls Law Undersirable\nSuch proposals as the Cham\nber's for \u201cright-to-work\" laws/\nthe Council asserted, \u201care un\ndesirable and incompatible witn\nthe development of such man-,\nagement-labor relations as are\nin accord with public interest.\"\nThe statement issued by the\nCouncil said \u201cit should be\nmade clear that the (Cham\nber\u2019s) proposal would not pro\nvide work for any unemploy\ned, and that it would deny the\nfreedom of labor unions and\nemployers to choose the form\nof union security known as\nthe union shop, which is per\nmitted by federal law.\u201d\n\u201cIt confers not a right to\nwork,\u201d the statement added,\n\u201cbut a right to share the bene\nfits of organization without\nsharing its responsibility. A\ntruthful descriptive title\nwould be \u2018compulsory open\nshop,\u2019 not \u2018right to work\u2019.\u201d\nThe Council said it endorsed\nthe statement by the Executive\nBoard of the Division of Life\nand Work of the National Coun- i\ncil of Churches that \u201cunion1\nmembership as a basis of con-1\ntinued employment should be\nneither required nor forbidden\nby law: the decision should be\nleft to agreement by manage- j\nment and labor through the pro-I\ncess of collective bargaining.\u201d\n\u201cWe urse the citizens of\nOhio to reject legal proposals\nwhich will make either the\nopen or union shop compul\nsory,*\u2019 the statement con\ncluded.\nThis same point was made\nMarch 20 in the public state\nment by the six Catholic Bishops\nof Ohio. In their stand against\n\u201cright-to-work\u201d laws, the Bish\nops said they would oppose a\nstate law requiring union mem\nbership just as they are oppos\ning a state law forbidding a un\nion shop.\nThere is no state law which\nrequires the union shop. The is\nsue is determined in the free\ncollective bargaining process\nand by a vote of the workers.\nHowever, the Ohio Chamber\u2019s\nproposal would prohibit union\nshop agreements and make the\nopen shop compulsory.\nThe \u201cright-to-work\" campaign\nof the Ohio Chamber of Com\nmerce was also condemned re\ncently by Rabbi Abba H. Silver\nof Cleveland. Rabbi Silver call\ned the \u201cright-to-work\" proposal\na \u201cmisleading d e v i ce\" being\nused by \u201cpowerful business or\nganizations\u201d to destroy unions.\n'The Good Old DaysF\nHere\u2019s What Life Was Like Befoire\nUnion Organized Store Employees\nWhat was\nIt like before the\ndepartment store employees had\na union?\nThe management of Lasalle's,\nthe Lion Store and Lamson\u2019s\nwant the workers to help them\njo back to those \u201cgood old\u201d\ndays.\n\u201cI went to work at Tiedtke\u2019s\nin 1935 for $14 a week for a\n52 hour week,\" remembers Ada\nLong, a former president and\nbusiness agent of the Retail\nClerks District Council.\nNeedless to say, Ada Long,\nsince she remembers the pre\nunion days, is confident that to\nday's workers don't want to hit\nthe road back.\n******W\ngeetents)\n\u2018s\n\u201cYounger\ngirls were al\n7*\nF\nmi\nAda Long\n5\n7' ways being\nbrought in to\nreplace older\nworkers. Buy\ners always\nplayed favor\nites. Often it\ntook a pretty,\nface just to\nhold a job.\n\u201cWe had no\ncall-in pay and\nmany times you\u2019d have to wait\nfor days just to get a couple\nhours of work. When they had\nsales, they\u2019d flood the floor- with\nextras. The regulars would wind\nup doing stock work and the j\nextras would get the commis\nsions, if any.\n\u201cAnd the 52-hour week was\njust the starter. We had to re\nport a half hour early to set up,\nwash our own shelves, and stay\nfl an hour or so after closing to\nstraigthen up. There was no\novertime and if they were rushed\nat lunch, you got a short lunch\nperiod\u2014with no extra pay.\u201d _\nj\nSkit Flays\n\u2018Slave\u2019 Bill\nA group of enterprising UAW\nmembers in Region 2-B are using\nall the techniques of the stage to\ndramatize the lies of the pro-:\nposed Ohio \u201cRight to Slave\"\nbill.\nDuring a period of 60 minutes\nthe members of the Hobart unit\nof Local 128, Troy, O., use nar-1\nrators, actors, slides and charts\nto point out the moral and eco\nnomic aspects of the union shop,;\nand to demonstrate the falsities\nof the Chamber of Commerce\u2019s\nopen-shop proposal.\nThe program has so appealed\nto those who have seen it, that\nrequests for repeat performances\nhave poured in on Joe Kalmer,\neducation chairman of the Ho\nbart unit, who prepared the skit.:\nThe unit has responded to the\nrequests by offering to put it on\nbefore any group anywhere in\nthe state without charge.\nIn Toledo, the Dura unit of\nLocal 16 has booked the show\nfor a special meeting May 10 at\n8 p.m. in the Local 16 Hall, to\nwhich all union members in To\nledo have been invited.\nArrangements are also being\nmade by Local 497, Standard\nProducts Co., Port Clinton, for\nan early showing.\n1\nReno to Head County\nDelegation to Talk\nOver Sewer Problem\nState Rep. Francis Reno, a\nmember of the Metropolitan\nArea Study Committee of the1\nLegislative Service Commission,\nwill head a Lucas County offi\ncials delegation to Columbus\nFriday to discuss the sewer\nassessments law passed by the\nlast session of the legislature.\nBecause of the wording of the\nlaw, Mr. Reno said bonding com\npanies are hesitant about selling\nbonds for sewer projects because\nof the uncertainty of getting1\ntheir money back.\nThe law was written to give\nrelief to farmers on whose prop\nerty sewer and water lines would\npass.\nAlthough these lines would be\nfor development of residential!\nareas, the law calls for farmers i\npaying one-half the assessment\nand users paying the remainder.!\nRepresentative Reno is the\nonly member from Lucas County\non this blue ribbon study com-!\nmittee. I\nKNOX DUNLOP, Lion Store,\nputs it this way:\n\u201cI have belonged to the Re\ntail Clerks Union for about 20 i\nyears. It\u2019s meant vacations with\npay, commissions\nfor\nsales\npeo\ni Pe J Lvil1I11-000A0 -4 \u2014C-CB PCo\npie (including commissions on\nsales by management as well as\non phone and mail orders),\nshorter hours.\n_ overtime, regular\nwage increases, and sick bene-1\nfits.\n\u201cBut most important,\u201d\nsays\nDunlop, \u201cis the job security our\nunion won for us. In the union\nwe have strength. Without it a\nworker is on his own with no\nguarantee that he will have a\njob from one day to the next.\u201d\n\nJOSEPHINE MAROHN, a vet\neran Lasalle worker who is now\non the picket line, points to the\nfringe benefits negotiated by the\nunion including one which\ni proved particularly important to\nher.\n\u201cWhen I first worked at La\nsalle's, the union was just get\nting started. I was off sick for\nfive months and when I returned\nto work I came back as a new\nemployee\nwith\nno\nseniority. 1\nCPV-E wmi iiu S=--e-4\neven lost my vacation credit.\n4er. IOKA T 1\n\u201cIn 1956 I again became ill\nand had to be hospitalized. This\ntime I got $12 a day and part of\nmy salary through the union.\nAnd when I came back to work,\n'my hospital bill was paid and,\nthanks to the union, I kept my\nseniority.\u201d\nTHOMAS L. MAYS, a nine\nyear employee at Lamson\u2019s, re\nmembers the progress the union\nhas made for him, too.\n\u201cMy draw has increased by a\nthird since I started to work in\nthe store and the union won\neach of the increases. The union\nTOLEDO UNH\nON\nJOURNAL\nI\nMED EVERYWEEK IN TOLEDO\nN E WSPA P E\n\u00a3MA*\n20**\nTHE ONLY LA\n\nPUBL\nddype.., I\n5*\nIEs\n,188185423\n\n49*\n\n311\n4*\n5,\nx4.\nA\nA:.\n4\nI\nX\nVOL. 16, NO. 17\nPublished By\n425 Winthrop\nOrganized Labor\nSt., Toledo, OHM\nTOLEDO, OHIO, FRIDAY, APRIL 25, 1958\nPARYSKI\nPUs. co.\nStore NLRB Election\nDelayed By U.S. Court\nRetail Associates\u2019 plan to execute the Retail Clerks\nUnion in three Toledo department stores by means of an\nNLRB election, ordered although it broke long-standing\nboard precedent, ran into a snag this week.\nA Federal judge in Washington granted the Retail\nClerks a temporary order re-1,\nstraining the NLRB from con-1\nducting the election here\nApril 30. The judge reported\nthat he would set a hearing on\napermanent injunction as soon\nas possible but it\u2019s improbable\nthat the election can be held as\nscheduled.\nJohn Hull, NLRB regional\ndirector\nin\nCleveland,\nan\nnounced that he has ordered\nthe election postponed indefi\nnitely.\nThe Clerks have been seeking;\nto bargain with the stores indi\nvidually since Tiedtke's with\ndrew from Retail Associates in\nNovember and settled with the\nUnion. NLRB policy has been to\npermit managements to with\ndraw from associations to bar\ngain with unions.\nBy ordering the election, the\nNLRB denied the Clerks the\nright to bargain with the stores\nindividually, calling instead for\nan election in the three-store\nunit, covering workers at La\nsalle\u2019s, where many pickets have\nbeen replaced with new employ\nees, at Lamson\u2019s and at the Lion\nStore. I\nRelief from the election, how\never will be only temporary if\nthe Washington court denies a\npermanent injunction.\nIf the injunction is denied,\nthen the stores will again press\nfor the election in which they\nare asking the employees to help\nthem turn back the labor rela\ntions clock 30 years.\n\"They are asking employees'\nto vote Lasalle's workers out of!\njobs and to give up all the gains\nwon in 21 years of collective bar\ngaining as well as the security\nthey have earned through their\nUnion,\u201d points out Hugh Nicho-'\nlas, president of Retail Clerks'\nDistrict Council No. 6.\n\"Retail Associates, led by Ma\ncy-owned Lasalle\u2019s, planned the\nNLRB election to cap a vicious,\nunion busting campaign,\" he'\nadds. \"They think they will be\nable to trick the department\nstore workers into destroying the\nonly sure means of keeping the\nbenefits they have and of insur\ning future progress by voting\nthe Union out.\u201d I\nI Lion Store and Lamson work-i\ners, particularly those with long'\nI \u2014*s Pe-e-te-o--el wain ---t\nI service, however, were remind-!\nwon\nme\ninsurance, including\nBlue Cross-Blue Shield and\n$5,000 life. None of these things\nwould have been granted by\nmanagement if we hadn\u2019t press\ned for them through our Union.\u201d\nCATHERINE GRAY recalls\nbeing called into Lamson's be\nOeino caiied into \u2014amnon s dc*\nfore the union, sitting around\nfor hours waiting for assign\nment, and then finally getting\nan hour on the floor. All the\nwaiting was not paid, \u201cuntil we\nwrote the four-hour guarantee\nfor call-in into our Union con\ntract,\u201d\nsays\nthe ex-Lamson's\nworker who now is a Lasalle's\nstriker.\nI\nCLEM WALTERS, a steward\nand furniture salesman with 24\nyears seniority, sums it up this\nway for the workers:\nI was\none\nS\nof the original\n4 members when\nthe union was\nfirst organized\npt the Lion\nStore. We or\nt g a n i z e d be\n\nClem Walters\ncause manage\nment cut our\ncommission.\nWe got the cut\nrestored when\nwe organized.\n\"As a steward and a negoti\nating committee member, I have\nseen our union in action. I have\nseen grievance settled, job rights\nrestored, and back pay ordered\n.and paid because of unjustified\n(layoffs.\n\u201cWe have received countless\nbenefits because of our union af\n.filiation. We want to keep our\n(union and we want an honor\n'able and just settlement. No\n(thinking person can yote no.\u201d\nVMM\nThey Didn't Have\nUnion Contract\nEmployees of Every woman\u2019s\nMagazine had no union, figur\ning that they could get along\nwithout one.\nLast month, the 59 employ\nees of the magazine, which had\nbeen distributed to 1.5 million\nreaders through more than a\nhundred grocery chains, were\nnotified that they were to join\nthe growing army of the un\nemployed because the publica\ntion would merge with its\nchief competitor. Family\nCircle, after publication of the\nMay issue.\nEmployees -were offered a\ntoken severance payment on a\ntake-it-or-leave-it basis. They\nhave formed a committee to\nnegotiate but management has\nrefused to talk and the em\nployees are suing.\nThe employees report that\nmanagement has shown a\n\u201ccontempt for the rights of\nemployees\u2019* since the start of\nthe merger. Details of the\nmerger were kept secret from\nthese\nnon-union employees.\nuntil management chose to re\nveal them. One employee was\nfired on a day\u2019s notice and\nthen informed that she had\nresigned.\nNow that it is being \u201cli\nquidated,\u2019\u2019 the staff of the\nmagazine admits that it has\nbeen \u201ctraditionally an under\npaid, understaffed, overwork\ned operation.\u2019\u2019\naaaaaasaas**===============.\ning their fellow workers this\nweek that a no-union vote in the\nelection means throwing away\nall the progress they have made I\nI\nin 21 years.\nThe department store employ-]\nees formed the Toledo Retail\nTrades\u2019 Council in 1936, won a\nunion contract in 1937 and have\nnever failed to record wage and\nfringe increases and improve\nments in working conditions in\nsucceeding contracts.\nPre-union conditions were\npretty grim.\nWages were pitifully low,\nfringe benefits unheard of, and\na draw against commissions\nI wage plan for sales people us\nually left employees in the red\nwith no commissions.\nUnder the plan a worker,\nwould have a weekly draw and\nthen have to make a certain\namount of sales before he could\ncollect commissions. If the em\nployee didn't make the minimum\n(and they were so high that few'\ndo so regularly), the difference]\nwas held against him in sue-1\nceeding weeks, pushing the\nminimum still higher.\nWages climbed regularly with\nthe coming of the union in 1952,\nafter management provoked a\nstrike, the draw-commission def\nicits were wiped out by the\nunion. Since then deficits are\neliminated each week, assuring\nemployees a real chance for com\nmissions.\nWorkers Disregarded\n\u201cLabor relations before the\nunion in the department stores\nwere marked by the singular\ndisregard of the rights and dig\nnity of the individual,\u201d com\nments President Nicholas. \u201cJob\ninsecurity was the rule before\nthe union. Ask the oldtimers\u2014\nthose who can remember the\ndifference between the morbid\nconditions then and the senior\nity protection they won through\ntheir union.\u201d\nOne of the first gains in a\nunion contract points up how the\nunion looked out for the wel\nfare of the individual worker.\nThe first contract guaranteed\nlady employees time to get their\nhair done once every two weeks.\nBefore the union, workers\nwould be called in whether or\nnot there was work for them.\nThey would stand by, without\npay, sometimes for day after day,\njust to get a couple of hours of\nwork during the noonday rush\nperiod.\nThe union won, in its first\ncontract, a guarantee of four\nhours pay when individuals were\ncalled in, regardless of whether\nor not they were assigned work.\nFavoritism Was Rampant\nFavoritism was rampant. Top\nmanagement rode herd roughly\non buyers and buyers were ruth\nless in their treatment of employ\nees. Buyers found it easy to fire\n(Continued On Page 3)\nUnion Democracy in Action\n\u2014Union Journal Photo\nScenes like this one have been familiar as local unions\nand units elect delegates to the forthcoming state mer\nger convention which will start in Cleveland May 5.\nShown voting in their Unit election are these members\nfrom Champion Spark Plug (left to right): Lou Pfann,\nClyde Rauch and Bernice Keller.\n1\nSlump Still Continues\n\\To Move Downhill\nThe statistical evidence was\nmounting this week that the na\ntion's worst recession since the\nend of World War II is moving\ndownhill with the bottom not\nyet in sight.\nStatistics issued by various\ngovernment agencies reinforced\na growing body of economic\nopinion that a pick-up in activity\nmay not be in sight until the end\nof the year\u2014especially in view\nof the Administration\u2019s no-emer\ngency-action approach to the na\ntion's woes.\nFurther Declines Reported\nThe latest government reports'\nshowed:\nA further decline in industrial\nproduction in March to the point\nthat the Federal Reserve Board\nindex is now 13 percent below\nthe high point in December 1956.\nIn the two previous postwar re\ncessions the index drop never\nexceeded 10.5 percent.\nA further decline in retail\nsales, with a 2 percent decline in\nsales of durable goods and a\nmixed trend in other lines.\nA further drop in personal in\ncome with wage and salary pay\nments $1 billion lower in March\nthan in February.\nTotal income was off $300\nmillion in March from the\npreceding month. An increase\nin unemployment and social\nsecurity benefits and a rise in\nfarm income prevented it from\ngoing any lower.\nThe number of persons draw\ning unemployment compensation\nfor the week ended Mar. 29 re\nmained at 7.9 percent of those\neligible for payments\u2014the\nRetroactive Pay?\nOnly Through Union\nThe Retail Clerks Union has\ntaught one brand new word to\nemployees of Toledo department\nstores\u2014retroactivity.\nUnions, of course, invented\nretroactive pay. Without unions\nto negotiate wage increases,\nthere would be no such thing.\n(Of curse, maybe management\nshould get an assist. The stall\ning tactics at the bargaining\ntable on the part of management\nhelp the union pile up retro\nactivity.\nThe Retail Clerks Union has\nwon certain wage gains in these\nnegotiations. Management says\nthat it will put the wage in\ncreases into effect when the un\nion is out.\nVeteran Retail Clerks mem\nbers are pointing out to their\nfellow workers in the stores:\nAny increases management pro\nmises to grant are mostly to try\nto buy no union votes.\ni\nMost important: The only way\nthe workers in the department\nstores can guarantee themselves\nfair wage increases\u2014plus retro\nactivity\u2014full back pay\u2014 is to\nvote for the Retail Clerks so\nthe whole dispute can be set\ntled honorably at the bargain\ning table.\nAnd, were the union voted\nout, the result would be the\nloss of a lot of nice, welcome\nwords which, for the unorgan\nized department store worker.\ndon\u2019t exist\u2014words like: general\n.wage increases, retroactive pay,\nlonger vacations, better health\nand welfare benefits, job secur\nity, grievance protection, etc.\nfourth week out of five that the\npercentage remained at this rec\nord level\u2014highest since 1939.\nSteel, Auto Industries Down\nThe prospects for a pick-up in\nindustrial production were fur\nther dimmed by reports that the\nsteel industry is expected to\noperate at 47.5 percent of capa\ncity this week, a nine-year low\nfor a non-strike period.\nIn the auto industry wide\nspread layoffs continued and\nmanufacturers cut planned out\nput for the second quarter of the\nyear by about 100,000 units.\nDealers are reported to have\nmore than a two-month supply\nof cars on hand.\nMichigan, the center of the\nautomobile industry, estimated\nits unemployment at the be\nginning of April as 15.5 per\ncent of the state's labor force.\nThe industrial production, re\ntail sales and personal income\nfigures for March all showed a\nsharp reversal over previous\nyears when these indicators were\nheading upward in response to\nnormal spring pick-ups in activi\nty.\nIn the unemployment area\nAFL-CIO Pres. George Meany\nnoted in his letter to all mem\nbers of Congress that more than\n3.5 million Americans are work\ning far less than a full work\nweek, adding the equivalent of\n1.3 million to the 5.2 unemploy\nment figure. \u201cAs a practical mat\nter,\u2019\u2019 he added \u201cnearly 9.5 per\ncent of our labor force is job\nless.\"\nThis Week in City Council:\nWest Toledo Sewer Project\nTo Be Discussed April 30\nCity Council will have a\n\u201cshowdown\u201d with county offi\ncials next Wednesday over\nwhether the county seriously in\ntends to go along building the\n$3.5 million West Toledo sewer.\nOn that day Guy Neeper has\nbeen invited to appear before\nCouncil\u2019s Committee of the,\nWhole and explain the county\u2019s\nposition on going along with the'\nproject.\nl\nVice Mayor Ollie Czelusta\nurged that the sewer project be\nspeeded up to provide relief for\nresidents in the area who are\nbothered by flooding and to\nI\ncreate employment.\nHe criticized City Manager\nRink for not displaying leader-,\nship and taking the initiative in\nhaving the sewer constructed.\nChallenging Council to take\ntheir coats off and roll up their\nsleeves in pushing this project,\ncEveA in PUo--e uiis PTUJEee,\nMr. Czelusta called for quick\naction and said the Administra\ntion shouldn\u2019t be deterred from\ngoing ahead just because a tax\npayers\u2019 lawsuit is threatened.\nMayor John W. Yager de\nfended the Administration and\npointed out that the city has\nmoney available which it is will\ning to advance for planning but\nt. L. Ker eUe in\nso far has been unable to get\na definite commitment from the\ncounty.\nI\nCONGRESSMAN Thomas\n(Lud) Ashley informed Council\nToledo Delegations\nReady For Merger\nOf Ohio AFL, CIO\nDelegates from AFX. and CIO unions in Northwestern\nOhio were preparing this week to join union members from\nall over Ohio in creating a new merged organization.\nThe merger, which will bring together more than 1,\n000,000 organized workers in Ohio, will take place in Cleve\non May 7, following the final\nseparate meetings of CIO and\nAFL unions.\nSessions will be held in Cleve\nland's big Music Hall on the\nlakefront. The separate conven-\u2019\ntions will begin at 10 a.m. Mon\nday, May 5 for two days of\nwindup activities, and the dele\ngates will then join forces on\nWednesday to create the huge\nmerged body, to be known as\nthe Ohio AFL-CIO.\nFirst order of business for the\nmerged group will probably be\nratification of its new Constitu\ntion, worked out by the Execu-1\nfive Boards of the Ohio CIO'\nCouncil and the State Federation\nof Labor, AFL. Election of new\n.officers is expected to follow.\nThree Officers i\nThe new constitution calls for\nthree full-time paid officials of\nthe merged organization a\npresident and executive vice\npresident, both to be elected\nfrom AFL affiliates, and a see\nretary-treasurer, to\ncome\nfrom\nthe CIO unions.\nTwenty-four vice presidents\nare also due to be elected at the\nconvention 10 to be elected,\nfrom the AFL affiliates and 14\nfrom the CIO. The 24 vice presi-1\ndents and the three top officers\nwill constitute the executive\nboard.\nThe merged convention is due\nto adopt resolutions on many of\nthe urgent problems facing or\nganized labor in Ohio, parti\ncularly the unemployment situ\nation, the anti-union-shop pro\nposals, and the forthcoming No\nvember election for state and\ncongressional candidates.\nNumber Down\nWhile most of the CIO local\nunions in Toledo are sending\ndelegates, the current economic\nrecession is cutting deeply into\nthe number of delegates being\ncertificated. Some of the smaller\nlocal unions have been finding\nit difficult to finance the cost\nof sending delegates.\nLocal 12 UAW will send 29\ndelegates to the convention.\nThese delegates are advised by\nLocal 12 President Clem Hole\nwinski to meet at 8 p.m. this\nMonday, April 28 in Parlor A\nof the local hall at 425 Win\nthrop St. They will receive in\nstructions and elect delegation\nofficers.\nDelegates Listed\nFollowing is an incomplete\nlist of delegates from the Toledo\narea:\nLocal 12 UAW:\nAcklin Stamping Martin\n.Bachli.\n1\nthat he has introduced two bills\nin Congress for a public works\nprogram.\nThe bills would set up a Fed\neral Public Works Administra\nl tion to allocate funds and ap\nprove public works such as I\nschools, hospitals and highways\nin areas of substantial unem\nployment.\nCongressman Ashley's letter\nwas sent in response to a resolu\ntion adopted by Council calling\nupon Congress to embark on a\npublic works program to relieve\nunemployment and stimulate the\neconomy.\nIn his letter he declared:\n\u201cThat the economic recession\nhas reached emergency propor\ntions is a fact that seems appar\nent to everyone but the Chief\nExecutive.\n\u201cDespite his optimistic prog\nnostications weeks ago that the\n{recession has run its\ncourse\nthe latest unemployment figures\nindicate a further increase in\nemployment for the month of\nMarch.\n\u201cMy own feeling is that em\nployment can be stimulated if\nwe initiate an intelligent pro\ngram of public works such as\nschools, hospitals, housing, etc.\nThese facilities are urgently\nneeded I earnestly believe that\nan accelerated program of pub\nIlic works would do more than\nanything to reverse the eco\nnomic recession and return men\njtO work.\"\ndGGdGddGdddddddddddddaddddaaaad\nLocal 12 Convention\nDelegates to Meet\nLocal 12\u2019s delegations to the\n19th special Ohio CIO conven\ntion in Cleveland will meet in\nParlor A of Local 12 Hall at\n8 p.m. this Monday. April 28,\nPresident Clem Holewinski\nannounced.\nThe delegates will discuss\nthe issues which will come up\nat the merger convention, re\nceive instructions and elect\ntheir delegation officers.\nAuto-Lite\u2014Earl Stacker, Nor\nman J. DuPont, William Wol\never.\nBarrett\u2014Vernon Boulis.\nBingham Stamping Gordon\nPhillips.\nBuddies Lunch Thelma Ha\nworth.\nChampion Spark Plug\u2014Ches\nter Kaiser, Metz Strahm, Angie\nZoldowski.\nContinental Aviation\u2014Joseph\nKnapik.\nDeVilbiss\u2014Sigmond Zablocki.\nJones Laughlin\u2014Ted Mod\nrowski.\nMather Spring Benjamin\nRice.\nNational Supply Earl\nThompson.\nToledo Pipe Threading\u2014John\nAltmanshofer.\nSpicer Mfg. James Pifer,\nArchie Wilson.\nSpicer Office\u2014James Todak.\nSurface Combustion Walter\nWill.\nTillotson\u2014Helen Wagner.\nWillys Motors\u2014Richard Gos\nser, Charles Ballard, Michael\nBurke, Ray Wale, Steve Sadow\nski.\nSmall Shop Pool James\nStadler, Chester Szymezak,\nPaoline Woollard.\nLocal 14 UAW, Toledo:\u2014Wil\nHam Butler, William Green\nwood, Tom Russell, Paul Crunk\nilton, Frank Anderson, Harold\nBushey, Norman Schiffler, Geo\nrge Szymanski, alternate.\nOther Delegates\nLocal 48 UAW, Toledo:\u2014Joe\nWlodarz, Jesse Mitchell.\n1 Local 106 UAW, Lima:\u2014Joe\nSmith, Albert Denny.\nLocal 128 UAW, Troy:\u2014Art\nFagan, Joe Kalmer, Charles\nGnodle.\nLocal 348 UAW, Toledo:\u2014 1\nJohn Marion, Robert Bauchman.\nLocal 533 UAW, Fostoria:\u2014\nCarl Munger.\nLocal 711 UAW, Lima:\u2014Paul\nWood, Dennis Wita.\nI Local 750 UAW, Marion:\u2014\nEdward Moran, Charles Reid,'\nI William Darnell.\nLocal 773 UAW. Toledo:\nHerman N. Sperr, John P. Wolf.\nLocal 911 UAW, Delphos:\u2014\nRichard Grewe.\nl\nLocal\n975\nUAW, Lima:\n-Fur!\ni Williams, Harvey Bowersock,\nRobert Routson.\nLocal 990 UAW. Bowling\n|Green:\u2014Walter Arts.\nT _ 109F TTAW\nLocal 1037 UAW, Newark:\u2014\nVirgil Lake, Ivan Whyde, Jasper\nPuryer.\nLocal 1058 UAW, Toledo:\u2014\nErnest Love, Peter Zvara.\nLocal 1211 UAW, Lima:\u2014\nChester Dyer, Delmar Hampton.\nOther Unions\nLocal 11-346, Oil, Chemical\n'and Atomic Workers:\u2014Kenneth\n'Koch, George Jones.\nLocal 349 Utility Workers:\u2014\nRalph Butler, Ernest Sabo, John\nT. O'Connell.\nLocal 9 Glass Worker s:\u2014\nJoseph Gembus, Jack Miles,\nJames Gehr, James Rice, Frank\nLaubenthal, Frank Hornyak,\n'Tony Stevens, Jr., Ed Weagley,\nJohn Weaver, Edwin Gross.\ni Educational Unit\nI And TIUC Cancel\nRegular Meetings\nRegular meetings of two or\nganizations of labor in Toledo\nhave been cancelled this month\nbecause of the press of other\nbusiness.\nThe organizations are the Reg\nion 2-B UAW Educational\nLeague, which normally would\nhave met today, Friday, April\n25, and the Toledo Industrial\nUnion Council, regularly sched\nuled for Monday, April 28.\nf t","height":"26748","width":"19484"}}
